generics use the class name to find a function associated with that particular class (method) and executes it. For example, In the given image, when the 1st `print()` is called, `print()` tries to search for a function #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:16062022220046]

attribute, often times leading to unintended behaviour, S3 doesn't have any checks to prevent you from doing that. [see_image_1] To create an object of certain class, you can assign by using `class()` or using `structure()`. #RStats #DataScience [TimeStamp:16062022220046] https://t.co/LB53e8jW3q

[see_image_2] When you check the class of an object. The returned vector tells you the inherited classes and their order of inheritance. or in other words, "factor" is the super class & "ordered" is the sub class. [see_image_3] The order of inheritance is used when the object is passed to generic functions like `print()`, `plot()`, `summary()`.
